  <h1>What to Do During Divorce</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Gather and preserve financial documents</h2><p>Collect recent statements for all accounts: bank, brokerage, retirement, credit cards, mortgages, and auto loans. Obtain tax returns for the last 3&ndash;5 years. Get recent pay stubs for both spouses. Download or print before separation if possible &mdash; access to shared accounts may be cut off.</p>
  <h2>2. Do not dissipate marital assets</h2><p>Courts prohibit &ldquo;dissipation&rdquo; of marital assets after the date of separation: giving money to a new partner, running up debt, hiding assets in a business, or transferring property to relatives. Violations lead to sanctions and adverse crediting at division.</p>
  <h2>3. Understand temporary orders</h2><p>Early in the case, courts often issue temporary orders establishing who stays in the home, who pays which bills, temporary child custody, and temporary support. These are not final but set the tone for the case. File promptly for temporary orders if your spouse is cutting off access to funds.</p>
  <h2>4. Open individual accounts</h2><p>Set up individual bank accounts and direct your paycheck to them before separation is formal. Keep detailed records of what came from where. Do not spend down joint accounts precipitously &mdash; courts will trace it.</p>
  <h2>5. Work with a family law attorney</h2><p>Family law is highly state-specific. An attorney can advise on the best approach (uncontested, mediated, or litigated), help you negotiate from an informed position, and ensure QDROs and other legal instruments are properly drafted. Many offer flat-fee packages for uncontested divorces.</p>
